    "The full details and parameters can be found directly in [21], 'Section III.",
    "Weak Designs'.RSH 1-bit extraction: After using the block weak design to split the seed into m sub-strings, we perform m RSH one-bit extractions, where the one bit extractor is constructed from the concatenation of a Reed-Solomon and a Hadamard code (see [21], 'Section III.",
    "Polynomial hashing').",
    "Each one-bit extractor takes as input the extractor input x ∈ {0, 1} n and one of the m sub-strings of the seed y generated by the block weak design, y S i ∈ {0, 1} t for some i ∈ {1,..., m}.",
    "To implement RSH, the seed sub-string y S i is further split into two sub-strings of l bits, where the first is used in the Reed-Solomon step and the second in the Hadamard step."
